data.content:
end
End is the last time step plus a specified DELTA_T, which defines the conclusion of the data collection interval and cannot precede the start timestamp.<SEP>End marks the ending point of the measurement interval for calculating sampledSeconds.

overlapTraveltime
Overlap travel time estimates the duration for any part of a vehicle to pass the edge or lane, influenced by vehicle length and speed.

speed
Speed indicates the rate of vehicle movement, critical for estimating travel times and vehicle behavior on edges or lanes.

traveltime
Travel time is an estimation of the time required to traverse an edge or lane based on mean speed.

speedRelative
Speed relative represents the ratio of mean speed to the lane speed limit, indicating how fast the vehicles are moving in relation to allowed speeds.<SEP>SpeedRelative measures the actual speed relative to the speed limit, affecting timeLoss based on how much lower it is than the limit.

lane
Lane is defined as a single lane within a road segment, a lower spatial unit that cannot exist independently of an edge.<SEP>Lane refers to a defined section of roadway for vehicles, which is crucial for measuring laneDensity and occupancy.

begin
Begin defines the start timestamp of the data collection interval, crucial for establishing the timeframe of data.<SEP>Begin signifies the starting point of the measurement interval for calculating sampledSeconds.

edge
Edge represents a road segment that serves as a higher spatial unit in the context of traffic data collection.<SEP>Edge refers to a spatial boundary where vehicle density and occupancy are measured, integral for calculations of lane and edge metrics.

laneDensity
Lane density refers to the average number of vehicles in each lane, essential for understanding traffic flow and congestion.<SEP>LaneDensity quantifies the number of vehicles occupying a lane, influencing vehicle movement and decisions to change lanes.

entered
Entered measures the total number of vehicles that enter the edge or lane over time.

density
Density is the measurement of vehicle density on the edge based on average lane densities across all lanes.<SEP>Density is a quantitative measure of how many vehicles are occupying a certain area, such as a lane or edge.

departed
Departed quantifies the number of vehicles that have exited the edge or lane, impacting traffic flow.

waitingTime
Waiting time quantifies the total duration vehicles remain stationary due to insufficient speed.<SEP>WaitingTime reflects the time vehicles are halted, which can increase with higher sampledSeconds, particularly in congested conditions.

laneChangedTo
Lane changed to indicates the number of vehicles switching to a new lane, affecting lane density.<SEP>LaneChangedTo denotes the vehicles that have entered a lane, usually when its laneDensity is lower than that of adjacent lanes.

occupancy
Occupancy reflects the percentage of the edge or lane occupied by vehicles, impacting vehicle movement and speed.<SEP>Occupancy indicates the proportion of a lane or edge occupied by vehicles, important for understanding traffic flow.

timeLoss
Time loss is the total time vehicles lose when they travel at speeds lower than desired.<SEP>TimeLoss represents the additional time vehicles spend traveling slower than desired, which can rise with more sampledSeconds.

left
Left counts the number of vehicles that have exited the edge or lane downstream, further influencing traffic metrics.

laneChangedFrom
Lane changed from records the number of vehicles shifting away from a lane, which influences lane density.<SEP>LaneChangedFrom signifies the vehicles that have left a lane, typically due to higher laneDensity compared to adjacent lanes.

vaporized
Vaporized represents the number of vehicles removed from the edge, impacting overall vehicle counts.

sampledSeconds
SampledSeconds quantifies the total vehicle-seconds representing how long vehicles are present in a lane or at the edge.

teleported
Teleported measures the number of vehicles relocated from the edge, crucial for understanding shifts in traffic.<SEP>Teleported indicates the number of vehicles that have been relocated from a lane, impacting laneDensity by reducing the number of vehicles present.

condition
Condition describes the current state of traffic in relation to factors like vehicle speed, laneDensity, or congestion.

DELTA_T
DELTA_T refers to a specified duration added to the last time step to determine the end timestamp in the context of data collection intervals.

speedThreshold
Speed threshold indicates a specific speed level below which vehicles are considered to be halted, impacting waiting time.
